[
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Cousin's Wedding RSVP Avoidance",
    "id": "1-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client has a history of substance abuse and has completed rehabilitation, indicating a significant emotional journey. He reports ongoing family difficulties, especially with his mother, characterized by rejection and emotional neglect. He has struggled with obesity since childhood and has experienced bullying related to his weight. These experiences have likely contributed to low self-esteem, shame, and a sense of being unlovable or inadequate. The pattern of avoidance in social situations appears to be longstanding and connected to these early experiences.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I put myself in social situations, people will judge or reject me because of my weight and past. It's safer to avoid these situations than risk feeling humiliated or unwanted. I have to protect myself from being hurt again, especially by family.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "No matter what I do, nothing will change how my family sees me or how I feel about myself. There's no point in trying because I'll just end up feeling rejected and alone again.",
    "coping_strategies": "He avoids responding to invitations and withdraws from family contact to manage anxiety and protect himself from anticipated rejection or negative evaluation. This avoidance reduces immediate distress but maintains his isolation and reinforces negative beliefs about himself and others. In the past, he used substances to cope with emotional pain, but now relies more on withdrawal and avoidance.",
    "situation": "Received an invitation to a cousin's upcoming wedding. Has not responded to the RSVP request and has not answered follow-up calls from family members.",
    "auto_thought": "If I go, everyone will judge me for my weight and think I'm a failure. It's better if I just don't show up so I don't have to face their rejection.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "ashamed",
      "embarrassed",
      "sad",
      "lonely",
      "fearful"
    ],
    "behavior": "He ignores the RSVP request and avoids answering follow-up calls from family members. He withdraws from communication and does not engage with the invitation.",
    "rationale": "\"The invitation to the cousin's wedding may trigger anxiety and fear of judgment or rejection, leading to avoidance behaviors.\" \"The ongoing family difficulties, particularly the perceived rejection and emotional neglect from his mother, may contribute to feelings of sadness, loneliness, and worthlessness.\" \"The longstanding obesity and bullying experiences likely exacerbate feelings of shame, embarrassment, and low self-esteem.\" \"The patient's avoidance of responding to the wedding invitation and follow-up calls suggests a pattern of withdrawal and avoidance in response to anxiety-provoking situations.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Family Tension Case",
    "id": "2-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The patient has recently experienced family tension, specifically related to a disagreement with their parents about a wedding guest list. They have become aware of similarities between their own behaviors and their father's, who is described as repeatedly seeking approval and unconditional love from family members. This recognition has led the patient to reflect on their own patterns and may contribute to discomfort or embarrassment. The patient’s family interactions appear to be characterized by a fear of criticism and a desire for validation, as evidenced by both their own and their father's behaviors.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I assert my own preferences and they are not accepted, it means I am not valued or loved by my family. I must avoid conflict and seek approval to maintain harmony, otherwise I risk being rejected or criticized. My worth is tied to whether my family agrees with my choices.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If my family disagrees with me or criticizes my choices, it proves that I am not good enough and will never be fully accepted, no matter what I do.",
    "coping_strategies": "The patient tends to withdraw from family interactions or avoid addressing the guest list issue to prevent conflict. They may seek reassurance from others or engage in distracting activities to manage their anxiety. These strategies provide temporary relief but maintain the cycle of stress and avoidance.",
    "situation": "Disagreement with parents regarding the guest list for an upcoming event.",
    "auto_thought": "They don't respect what I want; no matter what I say, they'll just judge me or dismiss my feelings.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "frustrated",
      "disappointed",
      "tense",
      "self-doubt",
      "embarrassed"
    ],
    "behavior": "I avoid bringing up the guest list again and withdraw from conversations with my parents. I seek reassurance from friends about whether my preferences are reasonable.",
    "rationale": "The report notes the patient 'may engage in cognitive processes that involve seeking validation and approval,' and 'might become defensive when discussing the guest list, fearing judgment or criticism from their parents.' Emotional responses include 'anxiety and stress,' 'frustration or disappointment,' and 'self-doubt.' Behavioral responses include 'withdrawing from family interactions to avoid conflict,' 'seeking reassurance,' and 'avoidance behaviors, such as procrastinating on addressing the guest list issue.' The core beliefs and intermediate beliefs are supported by the patient's recognition of their own and their father's patterns of seeking approval and fear of rejection. The coping strategies are drawn from the report's mention of avoidance, reassurance-seeking, and distraction."
  },
  {
    "name": "PhD Candidate - Project Progress Concern",
    "id": "3-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client is a PhD candidate engaged in scientific research, working on a sequencing-related study. They collaborate with a colleague named Kelly and are involved in a project with a senior scientist who has struggled to gain recognition in his career. The client is currently concerned about the progress of their PhD project. There is a strong sense of pressure to succeed, fear of letting down colleagues, and a heightened sense of responsibility, likely influenced by the senior scientist's lack of recognition.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable",
      "I am incompetent"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I don't make significant progress on my PhD project, others will see me as incompetent and I will let down my colleagues. I must always produce meaningful results to be respected and valued. If I struggle or fall behind, it means I am not good enough for this field.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I can't keep up with the demands of my PhD project, it proves that I am not cut out for this work and that my efforts are pointless. No matter how hard I try, I will never be able to meet expectations or achieve recognition.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to avoid working on challenging parts of the project and procrastinates when feeling overwhelmed. They seek reassurance from colleagues like Kelly to validate their efforts. Perfectionistic behaviors are evident, as the client strives for flawless execution, which can lead to burnout and decreased productivity.",
    "situation": "Working on a PhD project and concerned about its progress.",
    "auto_thought": "I'm falling behind and my project isn't good enough. If I don't fix this soon, everyone will see that I'm not capable.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "stressed",
      "frustrated",
      "overwhelmed",
      "worried",
      "fearful"
    ],
    "behavior": "I put off working on the project and avoid discussing my progress with others. I check in with Kelly for reassurance and spend extra time trying to perfect small details instead of moving forward.",
    "rationale": "\"The patient is experiencing significant concern regarding the progress of their PhD project.\" \"The pressure to succeed in their research may lead to feelings of being overwhelmed and worried about meeting expectations.\" \"The patient may engage in ruminative thinking, focusing on potential negative outcomes and perceived inadequacies in their research progress.\" \"In response to their concerns, the patient might exhibit avoidance behaviors, such as procrastinating on tasks related to their project or avoiding discussions about their progress. They may also seek reassurance from colleagues, like Kelly, to validate their efforts and to gain a sense of support. The patient might engage in perfectionistic behaviors, striving for flawless execution of their research tasks, which could lead to burnout and decreased productivity.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization Diagram",
    "id": "4-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "Case Formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client recently underwent shoulder surgery and is experiencing a painful recovery. They have ongoing pain, numbness, and tingling from a herniated cervical disc. There is a history of physical therapy for walking difficulties and back issues, as well as a past prolonged illness that led to immobility. After starting a new relationship, the client experienced a return of physical symptoms. These repeated health setbacks and periods of immobility may have contributed to a sense of vulnerability and anticipatory anxiety about their physical health and ability to function.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am incompetent"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I experience new or worsening physical symptoms, it means I am losing control over my health and I won't be able to cope. If my health declines again, I will become a burden to others and unable to participate in life as I want. I must always be vigilant for signs that my body is failing, or I will be caught off guard and unable to manage.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If my health keeps getting worse no matter what I do, there is no point in trying and I will end up stuck and helpless again.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client seeks reassurance from their therapist after receiving distressing medical news. They may avoid physical activities or social situations that could worsen symptoms. There is a tendency to ruminate on health issues and withdraw when feeling overwhelmed by pain or uncertainty.",
    "situation": "Received an MRI report indicating a herniated disc. Contacted the therapist after receiving the report.",
    "auto_thought": "This means my body is breaking down again. I'm never going to get better, and I can't handle going through this all over.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "worried",
      "helpless",
      "frustrated",
      "fearful",
      "disappointed"
    ],
    "behavior": "Immediately contacted the therapist for reassurance. Withdrew from activities to avoid making symptoms worse. Spent time ruminating about the implications of the MRI report.",
    "rationale": "\"The MRI report indicating a herniated disc could trigger thoughts of worst-case scenarios regarding their health and mobility.\" \"The ongoing pain and discomfort from the herniated cervical disc may exacerbate these emotions, leading to increased anxiety and worry about their physical health and future mobility.\" \"The patient may engage in avoidance behaviors, such as withdrawing from physical activities or social interactions that they perceive as potentially exacerbating their symptoms.\" \"They might also seek reassurance from medical professionals or their therapist to alleviate anxiety about their health.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Website Project Client",
    "id": "5-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client has a history of working overseas and building a website related to that work. He frequently starts new projects with enthusiasm but tends to abandon them when difficulties arise, indicating a pattern of withdrawal in the face of obstacles. There is a significant family-related difficulty involving his father, for which he wrote a personal letter as part of a forgiveness process. This suggests he is capable of reflective emotional processing and is motivated to resolve interpersonal conflicts.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable",
      "I am a failure, loser"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I encounter obstacles in my projects, it means I'm not capable enough to succeed, so it's better to stop before I fail completely. If things don't go smoothly, it shows that I'm not cut out for this. I should avoid pushing through difficulties to protect myself from feeling like a failure.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I can't get past these challenges, it proves that I'm a failure and nothing I do will work out, so there's no point in trying anymore.",
    "coping_strategies": "When faced with difficulties in his projects, the client tends to withdraw and abandon the effort, which provides temporary relief from stress but reinforces avoidance. He also uses reflective writing, as seen in the letter to his father, to process complex emotions and seek closure in interpersonal conflicts.",
    "situation": "Working on a personal project involving the development of a website.",
    "auto_thought": "This is getting too hard; I probably won't be able to finish it. If I keep struggling, I'll just end up failing again.",
    "emotion": [
      "frustrated",
      "disappointed",
      "self-doubt",
      "anxious",
      "discouraged"
    ],
    "behavior": "I stop working on the website and leave the project unfinished. I avoid looking at the project or thinking about it further.",
    "rationale": "The report notes, 'He appears to struggle with perseverance when encountering obstacles, often leading to the abandonment of projects.' It also states, 'This pattern may reflect a cognitive style characterized by high initial motivation and enthusiasm, followed by discouragement and withdrawal when faced with challenges.' Emotional reactions include 'frustration, disappointment, and self-doubt when difficulties arise,' and the behavioral response is described as 'a pattern of avoidance when faced with challenges.' The coping strategy of withdrawal is highlighted: 'The patient appears to cope with project-related difficulties by withdrawing and abandoning efforts, which may provide temporary relief from stress but ultimately reinforces a cycle of avoidance.'"
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization Diagram for 28-year-old Student",
    "id": "6-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "Case Formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client is a 28-year-old student who has recently returned from Egypt and is now managing bills, finances, and health insurance independently for the first time, after previously relying on parental support. Their brother continues to be financially dependent on their parents. The client is considering asking their parents for financial help and is seeking affordable counseling services. This transition appears to be emotionally challenging, with the client experiencing anxiety and self-doubt about their ability to manage these new responsibilities.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [],
    "worthless_belief": [
      "I am worthless, waste"
    ],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I ask my parents for help, it means I haven't really grown up and can't handle adult responsibilities. I should be able to manage on my own, and needing support is a sign that I'm not good enough. Depending on others makes me feel inadequate compared to what I expect of myself.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I can't manage my finances without help, it means I'll never be truly independent or successful. No matter how hard I try, I always end up needing support, so maybe I'm just not capable.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to avoid or delay financial planning and decision-making when feeling overwhelmed. They may seek reassurance or support from parents, which temporarily reduces anxiety but reinforces dependency. The client is also proactively seeking affordable counseling, indicating a willingness to address their difficulties.",
    "situation": "Considering requesting financial help from parents. Looking for affordable counseling services.",
    "auto_thought": "If I ask my parents for money, it means I can't handle being an adult. I'm letting myself and them down.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "ashamed",
      "guilty",
      "overwhelmed",
      "worried"
    ],
    "behavior": "I hesitate to contact my parents and put off asking for help. I spend time searching online for counseling options instead of making a decision. I may avoid looking closely at my finances.",
    "rationale": "\"The transition from relying on parental support to managing finances independently can evoke feelings of anxiety, worry, and stress... The consideration of asking for financial help from their parents might also evoke feelings of guilt or shame, as it may be perceived as a step back in their journey towards independence.\" \"They might ruminate on thoughts of inadequacy or fear of failure, which can exacerbate feelings of anxiety.\" \"In response to these stressors, the patient might exhibit behaviors such as avoiding financial planning or delaying decisions related to their finances. They may also seek reassurance from their parents or others...\""
  },
  {
    "name": "Client A",
    "id": "7-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client has a longstanding pattern of working long hours in demanding environments, including touring work, which likely contributed to chronic stress and exhaustion. There are unresolved issues with the father, including past abuse, which have recently been brought to the surface through an exchange of letters. This recent communication may have stirred up complex emotions and memories, impacting the client's current functioning. The client is now attempting to focus on personal projects but finds themselves procrastinating and avoiding work by spending time on social media.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable",
      "I am a failure, loser"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I don't make significant progress on my personal projects, it means I'm not capable and others will see me as a failure. I must avoid situations where I might be criticized or judged, because it will confirm what I fear about myself. If I feel overwhelmed or anxious, I should distract myself to avoid feeling worse.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I can't even get started on my own projects, it proves that I'm hopeless and nothing will ever change for me. There's no point in trying because I always end up stuck.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client frequently turns to social media as a way to escape feelings of anxiety and inadequacy when faced with personal projects. This avoidance provides short-term relief but maintains a cycle of procrastination and self-criticism. The client also ruminates about unresolved issues with their father, which may further drain motivation and increase emotional distress.",
    "situation": "Evaluating progress on personal projects, including developing a website. Spending time on social media instead of working on the project.",
    "auto_thought": "I'm wasting time again and not getting anything done. If I keep this up, I'll never finish and everyone will see that I'm a failure.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "tense",
      "frustrated",
      "ashamed",
      "disappointed"
    ],
    "behavior": "I check my phone and scroll through social media instead of working on my website. I avoid opening the project files and tell myself I'll start later.",
    "rationale": "\"The tendency to spend time on social media instead of working on personal projects could be a form of avoidance, possibly stemming from fear of failure or criticism... This avoidance can lead to procrastination and a lack of progress on personal goals, which may further exacerbate feelings of frustration and disappointment.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "Client with trauma history and relationship trust issues",
    "id": "8-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "Trauma",
      "Relationship"
    ],
    "history": "The client experienced a traumatic sexual assault by her partner, Ivan, which has led to ongoing difficulties with trust and intimacy in their relationship. She reports that Ivan is making efforts to rebuild trust, and there has been some improvement in their dynamic. The resumption of physical intimacy is occurring in the context of this complex history, and the client is likely to experience a mix of hope and skepticism about these changes.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I let myself be physically intimate again, I might get hurt or betrayed, because I can't fully trust Ivan yet. I need to be constantly on guard to protect myself from being vulnerable. If I let my guard down, something bad could happen again.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I try to trust and things go wrong again, it will prove that I can't ever be safe or happy in this relationship. No matter what I do, I can't escape feeling anxious and doubtful about intimacy.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to avoid or withdraw from physical intimacy when feeling anxious or unsafe. She may seek reassurance from Ivan or test boundaries to monitor his trustworthiness. At times, she may emotionally numb herself or oscillate between open communication and withdrawal, depending on her emotional state.",
    "situation": "Physical intimacy is resuming in the relationship.",
    "auto_thought": "What if Ivan hurts me again? I can't be sure he's really changed.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "fearful",
      "vulnerable",
      "hopeful",
      "doubtful"
    ],
    "behavior": "She hesitates or pulls away during intimate moments. She may ask Ivan for reassurance or closely watch his reactions. Sometimes she emotionally distances herself to cope with the anxiety.",
    "rationale": "\"The resumption of physical intimacy may trigger these emotions, leading to heightened anxiety or fear.\" \"She may experience intrusive thoughts related to the assault, which could manifest as flashbacks or heightened vigilance during intimate moments.\" \"Trust issues may lead to cognitive distortions, such as catastrophizing or overgeneralizing, where the patient might anticipate negative outcomes based on past experiences.\" \"Behaviorally, the patient might exhibit avoidance of situations that trigger memories of the trauma, such as certain forms of physical intimacy.\" \"The patient might also engage in reassurance-seeking behaviors, looking for validation from Ivan to confirm his commitment to change.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Jersey Support Case",
    "id": "9-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The patient has a long-standing friendship with Jersey and has consistently provided support during Jersey's medical procedures and recovery, indicating a pattern of loyalty and responsibility. There is also an ongoing conflict with roommate Ashby over household issues, which is a source of chronic stress. The patient tends to ruminate about both Jersey's recovery and the unresolved conflict, suggesting difficulty in managing competing emotional demands and articulating concerns.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I don't keep supporting Jersey, I am letting them down and that means I'm not a good friend. I have to manage everything myself because others are depending on me. If I can't handle all my responsibilities, it means I'm failing the people who need me.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I can't keep up with supporting Jersey and managing my own responsibilities, it means I'm not good enough and things will never get better. No matter how much I try, I can't make things right for anyone.",
    "coping_strategies": "The patient provides practical and emotional support to Jersey, often checking in and offering help. When it comes to the conflict with Ashby, the patient tends to avoid direct confrontation and may suppress their own emotions, leading to internalized stress and rumination.",
    "situation": "Thinking about Jersey's recovery while managing other personal responsibilities.",
    "auto_thought": "I'm not doing enough for Jersey, and if I mess up my other responsibilities, everything will fall apart.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "worried",
      "tense",
      "overwhelmed",
      "guilty"
    ],
    "behavior": "Checks in on Jersey or offers help, even when busy. Delays or avoids addressing other personal or household tasks. Ruminates about both Jersey's situation and their own responsibilities.",
    "rationale": "\"The patient's emotional landscape is likely characterized by a mix of concern, stress, and perhaps a sense of obligation... This concern might manifest as anxiety or tension, particularly when coupled with the patient's other responsibilities.\" \"The patient may engage in ruminative thinking, particularly about Jersey's recovery and the unresolved conflict with Ashby.\" \"The patient likely exhibits supportive behaviors towards Jersey, such as checking in, offering assistance, or providing emotional support.\" \"The patient might also engage in avoidance or withdrawal behaviors regarding the conflict with Ashby, as ongoing disputes can lead to a reluctance to confront the issue directly.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Post-Divorce Adjustment",
    "id": "10-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "Case Formulation",
      "CCD"
    ],
    "history": "The client recently went through a divorce, which has led to significant life changes including financial struggles and the need to adjust to single life. They are co-parenting, which adds complexity and stress. Multiple friendships have deteriorated since the divorce, increasing feelings of isolation. The client also reports a complicated relationship with their parents, which may contribute to ongoing emotional distress and difficulty seeking support.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I can't manage my finances perfectly after the divorce, it means I'm failing at being independent and others will see me as incapable. I must not make mistakes or I'll prove that I can't handle life on my own. If I show I'm struggling, people will distance themselves even more.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I keep struggling with these financial problems, it just proves that things will never get better for me and I'm destined to be alone and overwhelmed.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to avoid or delay dealing with financial paperwork, feeling overwhelmed and anxious. They may withdraw from social interactions and seek reassurance from others about financial decisions, but also hesitate to reach out due to fear of burdening others or being judged.",
    "situation": "Managing financial hardship following the divorce, including handling financial paperwork.",
    "auto_thought": "I'm never going to get this right. If I mess up, it will just prove I can't handle life on my own.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "overwhelmed",
      "worried",
      "ashamed",
      "sad"
    ],
    "behavior": "I put off working on the financial paperwork. I avoid opening bills or emails about finances. Sometimes I ask others for advice, but I feel embarrassed doing so.",
    "rationale": "The report notes the client may experience 'persistent thoughts about what went wrong in the marriage or concerns about financial stability,' and that 'the financial paperwork might trigger thoughts of being overwhelmed or inadequacy, potentially leading to procrastination or avoidance behaviors.' Emotional reactions include 'feelings of anxiety and worry, particularly concerning financial stability and future security,' and 'feelings of sadness, loneliness, and perhaps a sense of loss.' The client 'might withdraw from social interactions' and 'avoidance behaviors, such as delaying financial paperwork or seeking reassurance from others about financial decisions.' Core beliefs are supported by themes of powerlessness, inadequacy, and fear of abandonment or judgment, as described in the report's psychological interpretation and emotional impact sections."
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Client A",
    "id": "11-1",
    "type": [
      "depression",
      "interpersonal",
      "relapse"
    ],
    "history": "The client has experienced chronic depression and isolation since late adolescence, with ongoing difficulties forming and maintaining friendships. A recent breakup preceded a depressive relapse, and the client has a history of using SSRIs, with recent medication adjustments. The pattern of isolation and negative self-evaluation appears longstanding, and the breakup likely intensified feelings of rejection and hopelessness.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [
      "I am worthless, waste"
    ],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I open up about my struggles, people will see me as weak or burdensome, so it's safer to keep things to myself. If I let people get close, I'll end up being rejected or hurt again. I have to protect myself by not expecting support from others.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I reach out or try to connect, it won't matter because nothing will change and I'll just end up feeling more alone. There's no point in trying because I'm destined to be isolated.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to withdraw from social interactions and isolate themselves when distressed, which maintains feelings of loneliness and depression. They sometimes ruminate on negative thoughts and avoid new social situations out of fear of rejection. Recently, they have begun to seek support by talking to a friend about their mental health, which is a more adaptive coping attempt.",
    "situation": "Engaged in a conversation with a friend about mental health struggles.",
    "auto_thought": "I'm just burdening them with my problems. They're probably thinking less of me now.",
    "emotion": [
      "ashamed",
      "anxious",
      "worried",
      "sad",
      "vulnerable"
    ],
    "behavior": "I hesitate to share too much and keep some things to myself. I downplay how bad I'm feeling. After the conversation, I withdraw and avoid reaching out again for a while.",
    "rationale": "\"The patient's history of isolation and chronic depression suggests a tendency towards negative automatic thoughts and cognitive distortions, such as all-or-nothing thinking and overgeneralization.\" \"The patient likely experiences a range of emotions including sadness, loneliness, and possibly feelings of rejection following the breakup.\" \"The patient's history of isolation may lead to withdrawal from social interactions, which can perpetuate feelings of loneliness and depression.\" \"The patient's engagement in conversations about mental health with a friend reflects an adaptive coping strategy, utilizing social support to manage emotional distress.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "Jazz Group PhD Student",
    "id": "12-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client is a PhD student in a science field who has a deep involvement in music. They previously led a college band and currently participate in a jazz group, but declined a leadership position in the group. The client reports ongoing mental health struggles and feels disconnected from colleagues in their scientific work environment due to differing values and work habits. This sense of disconnection and avoidance of leadership may contribute to feelings of isolation and self-doubt, as suggested by their reluctance to take on new responsibilities and their emotional response to challenges in music rehearsals.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I struggle or need repeated attempts to progress, others will see me as incompetent and I will let them down. I need to perform well to be accepted and valued by the group. If I can't keep up, it means I'm not cut out for this and shouldn't take on more responsibility.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I keep struggling and can't improve, it proves that I'm not good enough and things won't get better no matter how hard I try.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to avoid situations that might increase stress or anxiety, such as declining leadership roles and withdrawing from colleagues. They may also procrastinate or avoid practicing when facing difficulty in rehearsals, using avoidance to manage feelings of inadequacy and fear of failure.",
    "situation": "Experiencing difficulty during jazz rehearsals, requiring repeated attempts to progress.",
    "auto_thought": "I'm messing this up again. Everyone must think I'm not good enough to be here.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "self-doubt",
      "embarrassed",
      "disappointed",
      "frustrated",
      "ashamed"
    ],
    "behavior": "I hesitate during rehearsal and avoid making eye contact with others. I become quieter and stop volunteering to play solos. After rehearsal, I leave quickly and avoid talking to group members.",
    "rationale": "The report notes the client feels anxiety and self-doubt during rehearsals, particularly when struggling to progress, and fears judgment from peers ('anticipatory anxiety about their performance in rehearsals, fearing judgment from peers or self-imposed standards'). The client is described as withdrawing from social interactions and avoiding situations that might increase stress or anxiety, such as declining leadership roles and possibly avoiding practice ('the patient may withdraw from social interactions with colleagues due to feelings of disconnection' and 'the decision to decline the leadership position in the jazz group suggests a tendency to avoid situations that might increase stress or anxiety'). The emotional themes of inadequacy, disappointment, and embarrassment are highlighted in the report ('feelings of inadequacy or disappointment, especially given their previous leadership role in a college band'). The intermediate beliefs and core beliefs are supported by the client's patterns of self-criticism, negative self-evaluation, and fear of not measuring up ('negative self-evaluation and thoughts of not measuring up to their peers')."
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Conceptualization for Grief and Guilt after Loss of Aunt",
    "id": "13-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "Cognitive Conceptualization",
      "Grief",
      "Guilt"
    ],
    "history": "The patient experienced the death of a close aunt, who was a mother figure. They were unable to fulfill her last request and were not present at her death. There is a longstanding pattern of prioritizing others' needs over their own, which may have contributed to their absence. The patient now reflects on memories with the aunt, especially the unfulfilled request, which intensifies their emotional distress.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [
      "I am worthless, waste"
    ],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I don't meet the needs or requests of those I love, it means I am failing them and I am not a good person. I must always put others first, or I am selfish and undeserving of their love. If I make a mistake or let someone down, it defines my worth.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I can't be there for the people who matter most, then I am hopeless and nothing I do can make up for it. My mistakes are proof that I am not capable of being a good person, so there is no point in trying.",
    "coping_strategies": "The patient ruminates on past interactions and the unfulfilled request, repeatedly replaying what they could have done differently. They avoid places or activities associated with the aunt to manage overwhelming emotions. They may immerse themselves in caretaking roles for others as a distraction from their own pain.",
    "situation": "Reflecting on memories involving the aunt and the unfulfilled request.",
    "auto_thought": "I should have been there for her and done what she asked. I failed her when she needed me most.",
    "emotion": [
      "guilty",
      "sad",
      "regretful",
      "ashamed",
      "anxious"
    ],
    "behavior": "I withdraw from situations that remind me of my aunt. I replay the memories and what I could have done differently. I focus on helping others to distract myself from my own feelings.",
    "rationale": "\"The patient's inability to fulfill the aunt's last request and absence at her death may intensify feelings of guilt and regret, potentially leading to self-reproach and rumination over missed opportunities.\" \"The patient may exhibit cognitive distortions typical in grief and guilt, such as 'should have' thoughts or overgeneralizing their perceived failure...\" \"The patient might withdraw or avoid situations that remind them of the aunt, as a way to manage overwhelming emotions.\" \"The patient may cope by ruminating on past interactions with the aunt, particularly focusing on the unfulfilled request.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "Financial Stress Case",
    "id": "14-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "Case Formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client has experienced financial difficulties after making questionable investments, which has led to increased reliance on their parents for financial assistance. There is a pattern of ruminative thinking about past financial decisions and their impact on the future. The client appears to struggle with feelings of shame and a perceived loss of autonomy, as well as anxiety about future financial stability. These emotional and cognitive patterns are maintained by avoidance and passive coping strategies.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I depend on my parents for financial help, it means I have failed as an adult and can't handle my responsibilities. I must be financially independent to be competent and respected. If I make mistakes with money, it proves I am not capable or trustworthy.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I keep making bad financial decisions, there is no hope for my future and I will always be stuck relying on others. No matter what I do, I can't fix my mistakes and things won't get better.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to avoid financial planning and difficult conversations about money, sometimes procrastinating or withdrawing from discussions with family. They may seek reassurance from their parents, which temporarily reduces anxiety but reinforces feelings of dependency and inadequacy. Passive coping, such as hoping things will improve on their own, is also present.",
    "situation": "Thinking about how past financial decisions may affect future plans.",
    "auto_thought": "I've messed up my finances and now my future is ruined. I'll never be able to recover from these mistakes.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "ashamed",
      "worried",
      "embarrassed",
      "helpless"
    ],
    "behavior": "I avoid looking at my finances or making plans for the future. I put off talking to my parents about money and hope the situation will somehow resolve itself.",
    "rationale": "\"Feelings of shame or embarrassment may arise, as the patient might perceive this dependence as a failure to achieve financial independence.\" \"The contemplation of past financial decisions and their impact on future plans may evoke feelings of anxiety and worry.\" \"The patient's cognitive processes may include ruminative thinking, particularly focusing on past financial decisions and their consequences.\" \"Behaviorally, the patient may exhibit avoidance strategies, such as procrastinating on financial planning or avoiding discussions about money with family and friends.\" \"The patient may rely on passive coping strategies, such as hoping for external solutions or waiting for circumstances to improve without taking proactive steps.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "Workplace Underappreciation Case",
    "id": "15-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "Cognitive Conceptualization",
      "Workplace Stress"
    ],
    "history": "The client has a history of ongoing workplace difficulties, specifically feeling underappreciated and unsupported. They have repeatedly experienced their ideas and suggestions being dismissed or not accepted by colleagues or supervisors. These repeated experiences have likely contributed to feelings of inadequacy and self-doubt, as well as a sense of being undervalued. The ongoing lack of support and appreciation appears to have shaped their current emotional and cognitive responses to workplace situations.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If my ideas are not accepted or valued, it means I am not competent or respected at work. I must always have my contributions recognized to feel secure. If I am not supported, I am failing in my role.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I keep being ignored and unsupported, it proves that I am not good enough and nothing will ever change, so there's no point in trying.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to withdraw from discussions or hesitate to share ideas to avoid further rejection. They may procrastinate on collaborative tasks and seek reassurance from colleagues or mentors, but if this is not received, they disengage further. They sometimes distract themselves with unrelated tasks to avoid confronting workplace challenges.",
    "situation": "A workplace discussion about culture and atmosphere conflicted with a client meeting scheduled by the mentor.",
    "auto_thought": "No one cares about my input or schedule. Whatever I do, it won't matter because my needs are always ignored.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "frustrated",
      "overwhelmed",
      "sad",
      "discouraged"
    ],
    "behavior": "I hesitate to speak up in the discussion. I withdraw and avoid contributing my ideas. I focus on other tasks to distract myself from the conflict.",
    "rationale": "The report describes 'feelings of being undervalued and neglected,' 'repeated rejection of their ideas and suggestions,' and 'anticipatory anxiety, worrying about future interactions and the potential for further rejection or conflict.' It also notes 'avoidance behaviors, such as withdrawing from discussions or hesitating to share ideas,' and 'distraction or disengagement to manage their emotional distress.' These patterns support the selected beliefs, thoughts, emotions, and behaviors."
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Project Deadline Client",
    "id": "16-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation",
      "CCD"
    ],
    "history": "The client spent about a year working on a project in Europe, building a website and conducting interviews, and reports pride in this work as well as a wish to share the results. There is a past history of procrastination and anxiety, which has led the client to use strategies learned from a course and reminders to manage daily life. The client’s pride in past work suggests high personal standards, while the ongoing need to manage anxiety and procrastination indicates persistent struggles with self-doubt and avoidance.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I don't complete my project perfectly and on time, it means I am not competent and others will see me as unreliable. I must always meet high standards to feel good about myself. If I start to fall behind, it will spiral out of control and I won't be able to recover.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I can't keep up with my project and meet the deadline, it proves that I am hopeless and will always struggle with procrastination, no matter what I do.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client uses reminders and strategies from a course to try to manage tasks and reduce procrastination. When anxiety increases near deadlines, the client may delay posting portions of the project online, engaging in avoidance despite knowing it increases stress. There is a pattern of oscillating between structured coping and avoidance when overwhelmed.",
    "situation": "Working on a project close to its deadline with portions still needing to be posted online.",
    "auto_thought": "I'm running out of time and I won't get everything posted. If I mess this up, everyone will see that I'm not reliable.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "overwhelmed",
      "tense",
      "self-doubt",
      "frustrated"
    ],
    "behavior": "I check my reminders and strategies but still put off posting the portions online. I spend time worrying about the deadline and avoid opening the website to upload the content.",
    "rationale": "\"The pressure to complete the project on time might lead to feelings of being overwhelmed or tense.\" \"The ongoing need to post portions of the project online might trigger thoughts of inadequacy or fear of not meeting expectations.\" \"Given the patient's history of procrastination, they might engage in avoidance behaviors when faced with tasks that induce anxiety. This could manifest as delaying the posting of project portions online, despite the looming deadline.\" \"The patient's pride in their past work and desire to share it reflects a positive self-image and a need for external validation. The anxiety associated with the current project deadline might stem from a fear of not living up to past successes. This could lead to a cycle of procrastination, where the fear of failure or not meeting high standards results in avoidance behaviors.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "Sarah",
    "id": "17-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case conceptualization",
      "relationship distress"
    ],
    "history": "Sarah is in a long-term relationship with Amelia, who has a demanding professional schedule. Sarah feels isolated during the week and manages most household tasks, harboring unspoken resentment towards Amelia. She has a history of childhood separations from her parents, which were associated with distress. The report notes that these early experiences may have contributed to a heightened sensitivity to abandonment and a tendency to avoid expressing her needs directly.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable",
      "I am a failure, loser"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I express my needs or resentment, I risk pushing Amelia away or causing conflict, so it's safer to keep my feelings to myself. If I am not contacted, it must mean I am not valued or prioritized. I have to manage on my own because others won't be there for me when I need them.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If Amelia doesn't reach out, it means I am alone and will always be left behind; nothing I do will change that. Even if I try to connect, it won't make a difference because I'm not important enough.",
    "coping_strategies": "Sarah avoids discussing her resentment with Amelia and instead takes on household responsibilities to maintain harmony. She attempts to make contact with Amelia during the day for reassurance, but if met with silence, she withdraws further or increases her attempts to reach out, perpetuating her distress.",
    "situation": "Not receiving communication from the partner during the day and attempting to make contact.",
    "auto_thought": "Amelia isn't replying because she doesn't care about me. I'm not important enough for her to make time for.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "lonely",
      "sad",
      "resentful",
      "hurt",
      "frustrated"
    ],
    "behavior": "I check my phone repeatedly and send Amelia a message. When she doesn't respond, I withdraw and avoid bringing up my feelings when we talk later.",
    "rationale": "\"Sarah's cognitive experience is likely characterized by feelings of isolation and neglect. The lack of communication from Amelia during the day may lead Sarah to interpret this as a sign of disinterest or lack of care... Sarah likely experiences a range of emotions, including sadness, loneliness, and resentment... Her attempts to contact Amelia during the day can be seen as a strategy to seek reassurance and connection. However, if these attempts are met with silence, it may reinforce her feelings of neglect and lead to further withdrawal or increased attempts to reach out... Her history of childhood separations might also contribute to a heightened sensitivity to feelings of abandonment... Sarah appears to cope by taking on household responsibilities and avoiding discussions about her resentment... individuals in similar situations may struggle with expressing their needs and rely on indirect methods of coping, such as waiting for the situation to improve on its own.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "Anonymous Client",
    "id": "18-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "Case Formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client has a history of academic underperformance despite being described as intelligent, which may have contributed to ongoing self-doubt. They attended college but felt isolated, leading to dropping out with two years of credits remaining. The sense of isolation during college likely fostered feelings of loneliness and disconnection. The client faces financial difficulties and pressure from their mother to return home, which may increase stress and feelings of inadequacy. The mother’s high expectations appear to be a significant source of pressure and may have shaped the client’s self-evaluation and coping style.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I don't manage my time and achievements as well as my sister, then it means I'm not competent and will disappoint my family. I must always meet high standards to be worthy of approval. If I fall behind, others will see me as incapable.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I keep falling short and can't get myself together, there's no point in trying because I'll never measure up. My efforts are pointless if I can't meet expectations.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to avoid academic tasks and withdraws from challenging situations, such as dropping out of college and not addressing scheduling problems. They engage in negative self-comparison and rumination about their perceived shortcomings, particularly in relation to their sister. These strategies maintain their distress and reinforce feelings of inadequacy.",
    "situation": "Experienced an unproductive week due to scheduling problems. Comparing themselves to their sister's achievements and time management.",
    "auto_thought": "I'm wasting my time and falling behind again. My sister has it all together and I'm just failing.",
    "emotion": [
      "inadequate",
      "anxious",
      "ashamed",
      "disappointed",
      "overwhelmed",
      "sad"
    ],
    "behavior": "I avoid tackling my schedule and put off tasks. I spend time thinking about how much better my sister is doing. I withdraw from activities that remind me of my setbacks.",
    "rationale": "\"The patient may engage in negative self-comparisons, particularly with their sister, which can exacerbate feelings of inadequacy and self-doubt.\" \"The unproductive week due to scheduling problems might reinforce a belief of inefficacy, contributing to a cycle of procrastination and avoidance.\" \"Comparing themselves to their sister's achievements could result in feelings of inadequacy and low self-esteem, as they perceive themselves as falling short in comparison.\" \"In response to these emotional and cognitive experiences, the patient may engage in avoidance behaviors, such as withdrawing from academic pursuits and delaying their return to college.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "Rachel",
    "id": "19-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case_formulation"
    ],
    "history": "Rachel has a history of recurring relationship problems with her husband Ivan and ongoing work-related stress. She was recently laid off and is actively seeking new employment, which has heightened her stress and self-doubt. Her sister Emma often takes on a caring, supportive role, indicating Rachel's tendency to seek reassurance. Rachel's father, who had a successful career and strong work ethic, has shaped her high expectations for herself and her career. These influences contribute to her tendency to compare herself to others and experience self-criticism.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable",
      "I am incompetent"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [
      "I am worthless, waste"
    ],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I don't achieve as much as Ivan or meet my father's standards, then I am not successful and others will see me as inadequate. I must constantly measure up to others' achievements to feel worthy. Falling short means I am failing as a person.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I can't match Ivan's career or live up to my father's expectations, then there is no hope for me to feel good about myself or my future. I will always be left behind and never succeed.",
    "coping_strategies": "Rachel tends to withdraw from social interactions and avoids discussing her concerns with Ivan, which increases her isolation and stress. She seeks reassurance from her sister Emma, relying on external validation to cope with her distress. She may also procrastinate or feel overwhelmed by the job search, leading to avoidance behaviors.",
    "situation": "Comparing personal career aspirations to those of the spouse.",
    "auto_thought": "I'm falling behind compared to Ivan. I'll never be as successful as he is.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "inadequate",
      "ashamed",
      "disappointed",
      "worried"
    ],
    "behavior": "Rachel withdraws from Ivan and avoids talking about her feelings. She ruminates on her perceived shortcomings and seeks comfort from Emma instead of addressing the issue directly.",
    "rationale": "\"The comparison of her career to Ivan's could lead to thoughts of inadequacy or self-criticism, potentially impacting her self-esteem.\" \"She might ruminate on perceived failures or shortcomings, which can exacerbate feelings of stress and anxiety.\" \"Rachel might withdraw from social interactions or avoid discussing her concerns with Ivan, which could further strain their relationship.\" \"Rachel's reliance on Emma for support suggests a tendency to seek external validation and comfort during times of stress.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Work Blame Case",
    "id": "20-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client has repeatedly worked in environments characterized by micromanagement, which likely increased their sensitivity to criticism and blame. They report a tendency to self-blame in work contexts, suggesting a longstanding pattern of internalizing responsibility. This history may have contributed to their current cognitive and emotional responses when faced with workplace conflict or blame.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable",
      "I am incompetent"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I make a mistake or am blamed at work, it means I am not competent and others will see me as a failure. I must always be vigilant and responsible, or I will be criticized. If something goes wrong, it is probably my fault, even if I can't see how.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I keep getting blamed or criticized, it proves that I will never be good enough and nothing I do will change that. No matter how hard I try, I will always fall short and disappoint others.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to withdraw from colleagues and avoid tasks that might lead to further scrutiny. They may seek reassurance from peers or supervisors to validate their competence, and engage in excessive self-monitoring or perfectionistic behaviors to prevent mistakes. These strategies are intended to reduce anxiety but often reinforce self-blame and avoidance.",
    "situation": "Being blamed at work for spreadsheet errors that were not theirs.",
    "auto_thought": "They think this is my fault. No matter what I do, I always end up being blamed.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "worried",
      "tense",
      "ashamed",
      "embarrassed",
      "sad"
    ],
    "behavior": "Withdraws from colleagues and avoids discussing the error. Double-checks their own work repeatedly and seeks reassurance from a peer to make sure they didn't make a mistake.",
    "rationale": "\"The patient is likely experiencing a range of emotions due to the current work situation. Being blamed for errors they did not make can evoke feelings of being 'anxious, worried, fearful, and tense.' ... The patient's tendency to self-blame in work contexts suggests a cognitive pattern of internalizing responsibility, even when it is not warranted. ... In response to the emotional and cognitive impacts, the patient might engage in behaviors such as withdrawing from colleagues, avoiding tasks that could lead to further scrutiny, or procrastinating on work assignments due to fear of making mistakes. They might also seek reassurance from peers or supervisors to validate their competence and alleviate their self-doubt.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Anticipated Family Conflict",
    "id": "21-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "Case Formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client reports a longstanding history of family conflict, particularly with a dismissive and unsupportive father, resulting in estrangement. This background has contributed to feelings of being unsupported and misunderstood, as well as self-doubt. The client also experiences ongoing stress in their partner's family, especially with the partner's sister-in-law, Candace. Anticipation of interactions with Candace during an upcoming family vacation is a current source of distress.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned",
      "I am bound to be rejected"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I can't keep the peace or avoid conflict in family situations, others will see me as difficult or unworthy of support. I must manage my reactions carefully to avoid being dismissed or misunderstood. If I assert myself, I risk being rejected or causing more tension.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I can't handle these family situations, it means I'm failing and things will never get better. No matter what I do, I end up feeling alone and unsupported.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to avoid confrontation and withdraws from stressful interactions, especially with Candace. They seek reassurance and support from their partner, and may try to minimize exposure to conflict by limiting time with Candace or using humor to deflect tension.",
    "situation": "Anticipating interactions with Candace during an upcoming family vacation in Maine.",
    "auto_thought": "I'm sure Candace will make things tense again, and I'll end up feeling isolated or blamed. No matter what I do, it won't go well.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "tense",
      "apprehensive",
      "sad",
      "frustrated"
    ],
    "behavior": "I try to avoid being around Candace as much as possible. I seek out my partner for support and withdraw from group activities when I feel uncomfortable.",
    "rationale": "\"The patient's history of family conflict, particularly with a dismissive father, likely contributes to feelings of being unsupported and misunderstood.\" \"The ongoing stress related to the partner's family, especially with Candace, may evoke feelings of anxiety, tension, and apprehension, particularly as the patient anticipates interactions during the upcoming vacation.\" \"The patient may exhibit cognitive patterns characterized by self-doubt and questioning of their own feelings and actions.\" \"The patient may engage in behaviors such as avoiding confrontation, withdrawing from interactions, or seeking reassurance from their partner.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Patient (Ivan Case)",
    "id": "22-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "Case Formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The patient has a history of ongoing interpersonal difficulties with a partner named Ivan and his family. There have been recent issues around trust and betrayal, particularly after discovering Ivan made travel plans without consulting the patient. The patient continues to have contact with Ivan's family, which adds to the complexity and emotional strain of the situation. These dynamics appear to contribute to persistent worries about relationship stability and self-worth.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I am not consulted or included in important decisions by those close to me, it means I am not valued or respected. I must always be involved to feel secure in my relationships. If I am left out, it confirms my fear that I am not important to them.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I am repeatedly excluded or betrayed by people I care about, it means I will always end up alone and unloved, no matter what I do.",
    "coping_strategies": "The patient tends to withdraw from social interactions and avoids discussing the travel plans with Ivan. They may seek reassurance about the relationship or try to maintain peace with Ivan's family by accommodating their needs, even at the expense of their own comfort. There is evidence of ruminative thinking and attempts to distract from distress through external support or activities.",
    "situation": "Discovered that Ivan made travel plans without consulting the patient.",
    "auto_thought": "Ivan didn't even think to include me. I must not matter to him as much as I thought.",
    "emotion": [
      "hurt",
      "disappointed",
      "anxious",
      "excluded",
      "angry",
      "worried"
    ],
    "behavior": "Withdrew from Ivan and avoided bringing up the travel plans. Sought reassurance from others about the relationship. Tried to keep interactions with Ivan's family peaceful, even if it felt uncomfortable.",
    "rationale": "\"The trust and betrayal issues with Ivan may lead to feelings of being hurt, disappointed, and possibly angry. The discovery of unconsulted travel plans could intensify feelings of exclusion and betrayal, potentially leading to increased anxiety and worry about the stability of the relationship.\" \"The patient may engage in ruminative thinking, particularly focusing on the trust and betrayal issues with Ivan. This could manifest as persistent thoughts about the implications of Ivan's actions and what they mean for the relationship.\" \"In response to these emotional and cognitive patterns, the patient might exhibit behaviors such as withdrawing from social interactions, avoiding discussions about the travel plans, or seeking reassurance from Ivan or others about the relationship's status.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Family Visit Preparation",
    "id": "23-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The patient has a longstanding pattern of difficult interactions with their mother, marked by strained communication and a tendency to delay sharing significant events within the family. These dynamics have likely contributed to ongoing emotional distress and shaped the patient's approach to family relationships. The anticipation of parental visits tends to heighten anxiety and worry, as the patient recalls past negative experiences and criticism. The patient may ruminate on previous conflicts and feel misunderstood or undervalued within the family context.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I share important things with my family, I will be criticized or misunderstood, so it's safer to hold back. I must prepare for every possible conflict to avoid feeling hurt or rejected. If I don't manage the situation perfectly, things will go badly and I'll feel even more disconnected.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "No matter how much I try, my efforts to connect with my family won't make a difference, so it's pointless to hope for a better relationship. If I open up, I'll just end up feeling more alone and disappointed.",
    "coping_strategies": "The patient tends to avoid or delay sharing significant information with their family to minimize the risk of conflict or criticism. They may over-prepare for family visits and seek reassurance from others about how to handle anticipated difficulties. These strategies help reduce immediate anxiety but reinforce avoidance and maintain strained communication.",
    "situation": "Preparing for an upcoming visit from parents.",
    "auto_thought": "I'm going to end up feeling criticized or misunderstood again. No matter what I do, this visit will be uncomfortable.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "worried",
      "tense",
      "frustrated",
      "sad",
      "apprehensive"
    ],
    "behavior": "I over-prepare for the visit, rehearsing what I might say or do to avoid conflict. I avoid bringing up certain topics and delay sharing important news. I may seek reassurance from friends about how to handle my parents.",
    "rationale": "\"The difficult interactions with their mother may lead to feelings of frustration, sadness, and perhaps a sense of being misunderstood or undervalued.\" \"The anticipation of the upcoming visit from their parents might evoke anxiety, worry, and tension, as the patient may be concerned about potential conflicts or uncomfortable interactions during the visit.\" \"The patient may engage in ruminative thinking about past interactions with their mother, focusing on negative experiences and perceived criticisms.\" \"In response to the strained communication with their mother, the patient might withdraw or avoid sharing significant events with their family, delaying communication to minimize conflict or criticism.\" \"The upcoming visit from their parents could lead to behaviors aimed at managing anxiety, such as over-preparing for the visit or seeking reassurance from others about how to handle potential conflicts.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Client Invited to Sister's While Financially Unstable",
    "id": "24-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client has a longstanding pattern of experiencing pressure to perform and to manage social interactions successfully. They have learned to present a confident exterior and conceal their vulnerabilities, likely as a protective strategy against judgment or rejection. The recent business failure and resulting financial hardship have intensified feelings of disappointment, sadness, and shame. These experiences contribute to a heightened sensitivity to situations where their perceived inadequacy or vulnerability might be exposed, especially in family contexts.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [
      "I am worthless, waste"
    ],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I show my vulnerability or admit my financial struggles, others will judge me or see me as weak. I must always appear confident and in control, especially around family, to avoid being seen as a failure. If I let my guard down, I risk losing respect and acceptance.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I can't hide my struggles and people see how much I've failed, it proves that I'm not good enough and things will never get better. There's no point in trying because my failures define me.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to withdraw from social interactions or avoid discussing their financial situation to prevent exposure of their vulnerabilities. They maintain a confident front and may over-prepare for social encounters, while internally ruminating about their failures. Seeking reassurance from close family members is also used to temporarily alleviate anxiety and self-doubt.",
    "situation": "Invited to visit their sister while dealing with financial instability.",
    "auto_thought": "If I go to my sister's, she'll see that I'm struggling and think less of me. I can't let her know how bad things really are.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "ashamed",
      "worried",
      "tense",
      "embarrassed"
    ],
    "behavior": "I hesitate to accept the invitation and consider making excuses to avoid the visit. I avoid talking about my financial situation and try to act as if everything is fine. I may withdraw or limit how much I share during the interaction.",
    "rationale": "\"The patient likely experiences anxiety and stress related to performance, which may manifest as a fear of failure or inadequacy... The tendency to hide vulnerability suggests a fear of judgment or rejection... The invitation to visit their sister might evoke mixed emotions... it might trigger feelings of inadequacy or embarrassment about their financial situation... The patient may withdraw from social interactions to avoid exposing their vulnerabilities or discussing their financial situation... They might engage in behaviors aimed at maintaining their confident front, such as over-preparing for social interactions or avoiding situations where their financial status might be revealed.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Educational Staff Member",
    "id": "25-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client works in an educational setting with children who have learning disabilities. They report being pampered by their parents and experiencing minimal consequences for their actions earlier in life. There is a pattern of ongoing conflicts with authority figures, which may be rooted in their upbringing and difficulty accepting criticism or external control. The client’s professional challenges, particularly when outcomes do not meet expectations, appear to trigger self-doubt and rumination about their effectiveness and social standing.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable",
      "I am a failure, loser"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I can't get my students to participate as expected, then it means I'm failing at my job and others will see me as incompetent. I need to prove my worth through successful outcomes, or I risk being seen as less respectable. If I don't meet expectations, I will be judged negatively by others.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I keep failing to meet expectations, it means I'll never be good enough and things won't improve, no matter what I do.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to ruminate on perceived failures and seeks reassurance from peers or superiors to counter feelings of inadequacy. They may withdraw or avoid situations where their competence could be questioned, and sometimes fall back on familiar routines to regain a sense of control.",
    "situation": "Encouraging students to socialize and participate in campus activities, with results falling short of expectations.",
    "auto_thought": "I'm not getting through to them; I'm failing at this. Others will think I'm not good at my job.",
    "emotion": [
      "disappointed",
      "inadequate",
      "anxious",
      "ashamed",
      "frustrated"
    ],
    "behavior": "I hesitate to try new approaches and stick to what feels safe. I seek reassurance from colleagues about my performance. I avoid discussing the disappointing results with authority figures.",
    "rationale": "\"The patient's role in encouraging student participation, coupled with unmet expectations, likely results in feelings of disappointment and inadequacy. They may ruminate on these perceived failures, leading to a cycle of self-doubt and worry about their effectiveness in their role.\" \"The patient might also experience a sense of social comparison, feeling less respectable or placed in a lower social category due to their professional challenges. This could lead to feelings of shame or embarrassment, particularly if they perceive their role as less prestigious compared to others.\" \"In response to these emotional and cognitive patterns, the patient may engage in behaviors such as avoiding confrontation with authority figures or withdrawing from situations where they feel their authority or competence is questioned. They might also procrastinate or hesitate to take decisive actions in their professional role, fearing further disappointment or criticism.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "Client Exposed to Clinical Terms in Couples Therapy",
    "id": "26-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT Case Formulation",
      "CCD Model"
    ],
    "history": "The client has ongoing work-related uncertainty and anxiety, which contributes to persistent worry and tension. Recently, the client married Ivan, but the relationship included instances of physical abuse, leading to a separation. Despite the separation, both partners are interested in resolving their issues and are attending couples therapy. The client is now exposed to clinical terms describing the spouse's behavior during therapy, which may feel impersonal or stigmatizing and could impact self-perception and perception of the relationship.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned",
      "I am bound to be rejected"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [
      "I am worthless, waste"
    ],
    "intermediate_belief": "If others use clinical terms to describe my spouse's behavior, it means our problems are too serious or abnormal, and I must have failed to prevent this. If I am seen through these labels, I will be misunderstood and judged. I need to protect myself from being defined by these terms, or else I will lose my sense of self and connection.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If my relationship is described in clinical terms, it means things are hopeless and I am broken beyond repair. No matter what I do, I can't escape being seen as damaged or at fault.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to withdraw or avoid engaging deeply when clinical terms are used, possibly to protect against feeling judged or exposed. They may seek reassurance from the therapist or spouse to validate their perspective and reduce distress. Attending couples therapy reflects a proactive attempt to address issues, but emotional avoidance and rumination may maintain anxiety.",
    "situation": "Exposed to clinical terms used to describe the spouse's behavior during therapy sessions.",
    "auto_thought": "They're talking about Ivan like he's a case, not a person. If they see him this way, maybe our whole relationship is just a problem to be fixed or judged.",
    "emotion": [
      "vulnerable",
      "defensive",
      "anxious",
      "ashamed",
      "worried",
      "sad"
    ],
    "behavior": "I become quiet and withdraw during the session. I avoid making eye contact and hesitate to share my feelings. Later, I ask the therapist or Ivan for reassurance that things aren't as bad as they sound.",
    "rationale": "\"Exposure to clinical terms in therapy could evoke feelings of vulnerability or defensiveness, as these terms might feel impersonal or stigmatizing.\" \"The patient may engage in ruminative thinking... about the dynamics of the marital relationship.\" \"The patient might exhibit avoidance behaviors, such as withdrawing from discussions... to avoid confrontation or distress.\" \"The patient may also seek reassurance from the spouse or therapist, reflecting a need for validation and support.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Conceptualization for Recently Divorced Mother",
    "id": "27-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "CCD",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client recently divorced after a long-term relationship that began at age 19. She is now a single parent to a young son and is facing financial difficulties, particularly related to unresolved child support issues. She is adjusting to being alone and managing new experiences without a partner, such as traveling alone with her son and visiting family. The ongoing conflict with her ex-partner over financial arrangements has intensified her stress and sense of instability.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable",
      "I am a failure, loser"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I can't get my ex-partner to agree on child support, then I won't be able to provide for my son and myself, and I'll fail as a parent. I have to handle everything alone now, and if I struggle, it means I'm not capable. I must avoid conflict, but if I can't resolve this, it shows I'm not strong enough to manage on my own.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I can't resolve these financial issues and my ex-partner refuses to cooperate, it means things will never get better and I'll always be stuck struggling alone. No matter what I do, I can't change my situation and things are hopeless.",
    "coping_strategies": "She tends to ruminate about her financial situation and the unresolved child support, which increases her anxiety. She sometimes avoids addressing the financial conflict directly or delays responding to her ex-partner. She seeks reassurance from friends or family and may over-prepare for new experiences to manage her anxiety.",
    "situation": "Received an email from the ex-partner refusing to agree on child support and financial arrangements.",
    "auto_thought": "I can't believe he's refusing again—I'm never going to get the support I need. This means I'm going to be stuck struggling to provide for my son on my own.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "worried",
      "frustrated",
      "helpless",
      "sad"
    ],
    "behavior": "She rereads the email multiple times, feeling overwhelmed. She puts off replying to her ex-partner and avoids making immediate decisions about the next steps. She calls a close friend or family member to talk about how stuck she feels.",
    "rationale": "\"The refusal of her ex-partner to agree on financial arrangements could exacerbate feelings of frustration and helplessness.\" \"The patient may be engaging in ruminative thinking, particularly about her financial situation and the unresolved child support issues.\" \"In response to her current situation, the patient might exhibit avoidance behaviors, such as procrastinating on addressing financial issues or avoiding discussions with her ex-partner about child support.\" \"The transition from a long-term relationship to singlehood may also trigger thoughts of self-doubt and uncertainty about her ability to manage new responsibilities independently.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Job and Relationship Stress",
    "id": "28-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client has a longstanding pattern of self-criticism and is used to maintaining control and achieving goals. These tendencies likely developed over time and have shaped the client's approach to challenges. The current period of job searching and ongoing relationship and family conflicts, especially involving Ivan, have intensified feelings of inadequacy and frustration. The client's self-critical nature and high standards may have contributed to a cycle of striving for perfection and subsequent self-reproach when expectations are not met.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I don't achieve my goals or maintain control, then I am a failure and others will see me as inadequate. I must always perform perfectly to be accepted and valued. If I make mistakes or struggle, it means I am not good enough and will be judged harshly.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I keep failing at job searching and can't resolve conflicts with Ivan, then nothing will ever improve and I will always feel stuck and inadequate. There's no point in trying because I will just disappoint myself and others again.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to withdraw from social interactions and avoids job-related tasks when feeling overwhelmed by self-criticism. They may over-prepare or excessively plan as a way to maintain control, but this often leads to burnout. In relationships, especially with Ivan, the client may avoid conflict or seek reassurance, which temporarily reduces distress but maintains the cycle of self-doubt and avoidance.",
    "situation": "Experiencing difficulties with job searching. Dealing with ongoing relationship and family conflicts involving a person named Ivan.",
    "auto_thought": "I'm never going to find a job and everyone can see that I'm failing. If I can't fix things with Ivan, it just proves I'm not good enough.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "frustrated",
      "inadequate",
      "disappointed",
      "helpless",
      "ashamed"
    ],
    "behavior": "I avoid sending out job applications or delay following up on leads. I withdraw from conversations with family or Ivan, or become overly focused on planning instead of taking action.",
    "rationale": "\"The patient's self-critical nature likely contributes to feelings of inadequacy and frustration, especially in the context of job searching and relationship conflicts.\" \"The patient may engage in negative self-talk, characterized by harsh self-criticism and a tendency to focus on perceived failures.\" \"In response to these cognitive and emotional challenges, the patient might withdraw from social interactions, avoid job-related tasks, or procrastinate in addressing relationship conflicts.\" \"The patient’s self-critical tendencies may lead to a cycle of striving for perfection, followed by self-reproach when perfection is not achieved.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "Research Lab Client",
    "id": "29-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT Case Formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client has a strong identification with their research lab, finding camaraderie and a sense of accomplishment there. The recent departure of a close coworker has had an emotional impact, highlighting the importance of these relationships. The lab is experienced as a stable and predictable environment, in contrast to the client's personal life, which is described as less predictable and less comfortable. This contrast may contribute to the client's reliance on the lab for stability and their emotional response to changes within it.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I can't maintain stability and connection in the lab, then I will feel lost and unsupported. I need to be competent and prepared to keep my place in the group. If things become unpredictable, I must work harder to regain control and avoid feeling isolated.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I lose my sense of belonging or things keep changing, it means I can't count on anything, and I'll end up alone and unsupported.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client seeks reassurance and connection from colleagues in the lab and focuses intensely on lab-related tasks to maintain a sense of control. They may withdraw from social interactions outside of work and neglect personal needs, relying on the structured environment of the lab to manage distress.",
    "situation": "Preparing for an important discussion scheduled in January. Preparing for a lab meeting involving troubleshooting equipment and learning programming.",
    "auto_thought": "If I don't handle this meeting perfectly, I'll lose my place in the group. I can't let anyone see that I'm struggling with the new programming.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "worried",
      "tense",
      "insecure",
      "lonely"
    ],
    "behavior": "I spend extra hours preparing for the meeting and troubleshooting every detail. I avoid asking for help about the programming, and I keep to myself, focusing only on the tasks.",
    "rationale": "\"The patient likely experiences a strong sense of identity and belonging within their research lab, which provides a structured and predictable environment. The departure of a close coworker may have triggered feelings of loss and instability, potentially leading to thoughts of loneliness or insecurity about their place in the lab.\" \"The preparation for the upcoming discussion and lab meeting may involve increased attention to detail and problem-solving efforts, potentially leading to overworking or neglecting personal needs.\" \"The patient may be feeling a mix of emotions, including sadness and loneliness due to the coworker's departure, and anxiety or stress related to the upcoming discussion and lab meeting.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Disclosure Dilemma",
    "id": "30-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "Case Formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client recently completed an undergraduate degree and is entering the workforce. Within the last two and a half years, they came out to their parents and received negative reactions, which led to increased distance from them. The client moved to New York for education, using the opportunity to explore their identity away from family influence. The relationship with the mother is strained, with the mother focused on practical concerns rather than emotional support. There is also tension with a sister, who is described as envious of the client's independence and achievements. These dynamics have contributed to feelings of rejection, hurt, and a sense of isolation, as well as a pattern of withdrawing from family interactions to protect themselves emotionally.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [
      "I am worthless, waste"
    ],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I share vulnerable parts of my life with my parents, I risk being hurt or rejected again, so it's safer to keep things to myself. I need to protect myself from their negative reactions because I can't rely on them for emotional support. If I am open, I might just end up feeling more alone.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I try to be honest with my parents, it won't matter because they never really support me emotionally. No matter what I do, I end up feeling alone and misunderstood.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to withdraw from family interactions and avoids disclosing personal matters to their parents to prevent anticipated negative reactions. They seek independence and supportive environments, but also use avoidance to manage distress related to family rejection.",
    "situation": "Deciding whether to disclose a recent breakup to parents.",
    "auto_thought": "If I tell them about the breakup, they'll just judge me or make me feel worse. It's not worth opening up because they never really support me anyway.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "worried",
      "hurt",
      "lonely",
      "tense",
      "disappointed"
    ],
    "behavior": "Hesitates to contact or update parents about the breakup. Delays or avoids bringing up the topic in conversations. Withdraws emotionally and keeps personal matters private.",
    "rationale": "\"The negative reaction from the parents upon coming out may have led to feelings of rejection, hurt, and disappointment.\" \"The strained relationship with the mother, who is focused on practical rather than emotional support, might leave the patient feeling unsupported and lonely.\" \"The patient might also engage in avoidance behaviors, such as hesitating to disclose personal matters (e.g., the breakup) to their parents, to prevent anticipated negative outcomes.\" \"The decision-making process regarding whether to disclose a breakup to their parents indicates potential cognitive conflict, weighing the desire for authenticity against fear of further negative reactions.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Family Health Anxiety Case",
    "id": "31-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client has recently lost an uncle and a cousin, which likely contributes to ongoing grief and sadness. There is persistent worry about the parents' health, especially the father's multiple serious medical conditions. The client experiences emotional distance and tension with the father, partly due to the father's lack of transparency about his health. These dynamics may foster feelings of helplessness, responsibility, and unresolved emotional strain. The client tends to internalize stress and avoids direct confrontation, as implied by the pattern of distraction after distressing family news.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I don't stay vigilant and worry about my father's health, something bad will happen and it will be my fault. If I can't get clear information or help, I am failing as a family member. I must always be prepared for the worst because I can't trust things to turn out okay.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I can't help my father or change anything, then nothing I do matters and I might as well give up. If my efforts don't make a difference, it means I'm powerless and things will only get worse.",
    "coping_strategies": "After receiving distressing news, the client distracts themselves by watching television to avoid overwhelming emotions and intrusive thoughts. The client tends to avoid direct discussions with the father about health issues, maintaining emotional distance rather than seeking clarity or resolution. There is a pattern of internalizing stress and using avoidance to manage anxiety.",
    "situation": "Received a phone call from the mother regarding the father's health. Watched television afterward.",
    "auto_thought": "Something terrible is going to happen to my father and I won't be able to do anything about it. I can't handle this uncertainty and I need to escape these feelings.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "worried",
      "helpless",
      "sad",
      "frustrated"
    ],
    "behavior": "Turned on the television and focused on watching it to distract myself from the distressing thoughts and feelings. Avoided calling my father or asking more questions. Stayed physically and emotionally distant.",
    "rationale": "\"The ongoing concern about the parents' health, particularly the father's, may lead to feelings of anxiety and worry. The tension with the father could contribute to feelings of frustration, helplessness, or even guilt... The phone call from the mother might have intensified these emotions, leading to a need for distraction or avoidance, as indicated by watching television afterward.\" \"The patient may engage in ruminative thinking, particularly about the health and well-being of the parents, which can exacerbate feelings of anxiety and helplessness... The lack of transparency from the father could also result in assumptions or misinterpretations about the severity of his health conditions.\" \"The act of watching television after receiving the phone call suggests a coping mechanism aimed at distraction or temporary relief from distressing thoughts and emotions.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Father's Day Lunch Case",
    "id": "32-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client reports a long-standing pattern of strained relationships with both parents, feeling judged and disapproved of, particularly during their education. The mother's health condition is a source of concern, and the client perceives her as 'broken,' which may contribute to a sense of instability in the family. There are also unresolved issues related to allegations of a past affair involving the mother. These dynamics have led to ongoing emotional distress and difficulty trusting or feeling supported by their parents.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I go to family events, I will be judged or criticized, so I must be on guard to protect myself. If I let my guard down, I will be hurt again. I have to anticipate negative interactions to avoid being blindsided.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "No matter what I do, I can't make things better with my parents, so there's no point in trying to connect or hope for a positive experience.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client mentally prepares for the lunch by rehearsing possible conversations and anticipating criticism. They may withdraw emotionally or physically during the event, and seek reassurance from friends beforehand to manage their anxiety. They also use distraction or self-soothing techniques to temporarily reduce distress.",
    "situation": "Preparing to attend a Father's Day lunch with parents.",
    "auto_thought": "I'm going to be judged and criticized again at this lunch. No matter what I do, it won't be good enough for them.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "apprehensive",
      "tense",
      "sad",
      "disappointed",
