  {
    "name": "Cleo Case",
    "id": "33-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case conceptualization"
    ],
    "history": "The patient is involved in a complex romantic situation with Cleo, who is already in a long-distance relationship. The patient has taken on the role of providing emotional support to Cleo, especially when Cleo discusses her relationship problems. This dynamic has led the patient to feel caught between being a confidant and a romantic interest, contributing to ongoing confusion and ambivalence. The patient tends to ruminate about their position in Cleo's life and struggles to address their own needs directly, often focusing on Cleo's issues instead.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned",
      "I am bound to be rejected"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I am not always there for Cleo and support her emotionally, she will not value me or choose me over her long-distance partner. I need to put Cleo's needs first to maintain my connection with her. If I express my own needs, I risk losing her attention and affection.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "No matter how much I support Cleo, it won't make a difference—I'll always end up feeling left out and unimportant. Even if I try my best, I can't change my place in her life.",
    "coping_strategies": "The patient seeks reassurance from Cleo by being emotionally available and supportive, even when feeling insecure. They sometimes withdraw emotionally or avoid discussing their own needs, focusing instead on Cleo's problems. The patient may distract themselves with other activities to avoid the emotional intensity of the situation.",
    "situation": "During an outing, Cleo discussed relationship problems and sought emotional support.",
    "auto_thought": "I'm just someone Cleo turns to when she has problems—she'll never really choose me. No matter what I do, I'm always on the outside.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "insecure",
      "sad",
      "frustrated",
      "vulnerable"
    ],
    "behavior": "I listen to Cleo and offer her support, even though it hurts. I avoid bringing up my own feelings or needs. I later ruminate about my place in her life.",
    "rationale": "\"The patient may feel anxious and uncertain about their own position and future in this relationship... The patient might feel caught in a situation where they are both a confidant and a romantic interest... The complexity of the romantic situation with Cleo likely leads to ruminative thoughts... The patient might engage in behaviors such as seeking reassurance from Cleo or withdrawing emotionally when feeling uncertain or insecure... The patient might avoid addressing their own needs directly, focusing instead on Cleo's problems...\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization Diagram for Client",
    "id": "34-1",
    "type": [
      "case formulation",
      "CBT",
      "grief",
      "family conflict"
    ],
    "history": "The client lost a brother to suicide during childhood, which was a traumatic event. The family has ongoing conflict about discussing the loss, and the parents initially prevented the client from seeking talk therapy after the death. This likely contributed to feelings of confusion, sadness, and isolation, as well as difficulties in processing grief due to lack of support and open communication. The family’s reluctance to discuss the loss may have reinforced the client’s tendency to suppress emotions and avoid conflict.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I let myself feel or talk about my brother's death, it will only make things worse and no one will support me. I have to handle this pain alone because my family avoids it. Expressing my emotions will lead to conflict or rejection.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I try to talk about my brother or show how much I’m hurting, nothing will change and I’ll just feel more alone. There’s no point in reaching out because it won’t help.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to avoid conversations or situations that remind them of the brother or the family conflict, withdrawing from family gatherings or discussions. They may distract themselves with activities or suppress their emotions to avoid feeling the pain of the loss. These strategies help manage distress in the short term but maintain unresolved grief and isolation.",
    "situation": "Noticing that the brother's birthday is approaching.",
    "auto_thought": "I can’t let myself think about his birthday or I’ll fall apart. No one else wants to talk about it, so I have to keep it to myself.",
    "emotion": [
      "sad",
      "lonely",
      "anxious",
      "isolated",
      "tense"
    ],
    "behavior": "Avoids mentioning the birthday to family or friends. Withdraws from family interactions and distracts self with other activities. Suppresses thoughts and emotions related to the loss.",
    "rationale": "\"The ongoing family conflict about discussing the loss suggests that the patient might feel isolated or unsupported in processing these emotions.\" \"The restriction from accessing talk therapy could have led to internalized beliefs about the appropriateness of seeking help or expressing emotions.\" \"Behaviorally, the patient might exhibit avoidance of conversations or situations that remind them of the brother or the family conflict.\" \"The patient may also engage in behaviors aimed at distraction or emotional numbing, such as excessive work, social media use, or other activities that prevent dwelling on the loss.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Financial Stress Trigger",
    "id": "36-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client has been experiencing ongoing stress due to financial difficulties and unstable relationships. They are under pressure at work, having to manage technical issues and cover for an absent coworker, which increases their workload. Friends frequently turn to them for emotional support during crises, adding to their emotional burden. The client is considering asking their parents for financial help to pay for therapy, which coincides with an upcoming birthday and a planned visit with their parents. These factors contribute to a sense of being overburdened and emotionally depleted.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I can't keep my finances in order, it means I'm not capable and others will see me as irresponsible. I should be able to handle my own problems without needing to rely on others. If I ask for help, it proves I'm inadequate.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I keep failing to manage my finances, nothing will ever get better and I'll always be a burden to others. There's no point in trying because I can't seem to get it right.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to avoid directly addressing financial issues, such as procrastinating on financial planning or delaying conversations about money with their parents. They may withdraw from social interactions to conserve emotional energy and sometimes seek reassurance from trusted individuals, though this is accompanied by reluctance due to fears of judgment.",
    "situation": "Discovered that their bank balance was lower than expected.",
    "auto_thought": "I can't believe I let this happen again. I'm never going to get on top of my finances.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "overwhelmed",
      "ashamed",
      "worried",
      "disappointed"
    ],
    "behavior": "Stared at the bank statement for a long time, feeling frozen. Put off looking at other financial documents. Avoided reaching out to parents or friends for help.",
    "rationale": "\"The unexpected discovery of a lower bank balance may trigger thoughts of inadequacy or fear of financial insecurity.\" \"This cognitive pattern can lead to rumination, where the patient repeatedly thinks about their financial difficulties and potential consequences, which may exacerbate their stress levels.\" \"The patient's consideration of asking their parents for financial help suggests a potential internal conflict between a desire for independence and the need for support. This may lead to feelings of shame or embarrassment, as they might perceive asking for help as a personal failure.\" \"In response to these stressors, the patient may engage in avoidance behaviors, such as procrastinating on financial planning or delaying difficult conversations with their parents.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Work-Related Fairness Concerns",
    "id": "37-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client previously experienced a labor dispute at a former workplace, which has left a lasting impact on their current perspective regarding fairness, pay, and authority at work. This history appears to sensitize them to issues of justice and power dynamics in their present environment. The client tends to ruminate on past and current events, particularly those involving authority figures or perceived injustices, and this pattern is reinforced when reflecting on recent workplace situations.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned",
      "I am bound to be rejected"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I encounter a situation where authority figures respond dismissively or unfairly, then it means I am at risk of being treated unjustly again and my concerns will not be taken seriously. I must be vigilant and protect myself because I can't rely on others to act fairly.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If those in authority continue to ignore or dismiss my concerns, then nothing I do will make a difference and I will always be stuck in unfair situations.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to avoid direct confrontation about fairness or authority issues, possibly to prevent conflict or negative repercussions. They may seek reassurance from colleagues or document interactions to protect themselves. There is also a tendency to ruminate on perceived injustices, which maintains their distress.",
    "situation": "Reflecting on a work-related case and the response of a businessman involved.",
    "auto_thought": "Here we go again—he's just like the others, ignoring what's fair. No matter what I do, people in power don't care about people like me.",
    "emotion": [
      "angry",
      "frustrated",
      "disappointed",
      "anxious",
      "irritated"
    ],
    "behavior": "I replay the situation in my mind, analyzing what happened and what was said. I avoid bringing up my concerns directly with the businessman. I might talk to a colleague to check if they saw the same unfairness.",
    "rationale": "The report notes 'heightened sensitivity to issues of fairness and authority,' 'ruminative thinking,' and 'feelings of anger, irritation, and frustration' when reflecting on responses perceived as unjust. Behavioral responses include 'avoid direct confrontation,' 'seek reassurance,' and 'documenting interactions.' The client's history of a labor dispute and ongoing concerns about fairness and authority are explicitly referenced as shaping their current reactions."
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Client with Health-Related Work Stress",
    "id": "38-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "Case Formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client has a health condition requiring time off work for physical therapy. They have previously interacted with HR and a supervisor regarding their return-to-work and disability status. The client recalls a prior HR interaction during medical leave that left them feeling judged. This suggests a history of vulnerability and stress related to balancing health needs and workplace expectations, with a significant emotional impact stemming from perceived negative evaluation by others.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I show any weakness or need time off for my health, others will see me as less capable and judge me negatively. I must always appear strong and reliable to be respected at work. If I am perceived as a burden, I will lose my standing and acceptance.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I can't meet work expectations because of my health, it means I'm failing and there's no way to fix how others see me. No matter what I do, I'll always be seen as inadequate.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to avoid interactions with HR or supervisors to minimize the risk of feeling judged. They may ruminate about past interactions, replaying the experience and their perceived shortcomings. These strategies provide temporary relief but maintain anxiety and self-doubt about their workplace role.",
    "situation": "Recalling a prior interaction with HR that involved feeling judged during medical leave.",
    "auto_thought": "They're probably thinking I'm just making excuses and not really committed to my job. I can't trust them to see my situation fairly.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "embarrassed",
      "ashamed",
      "worried",
      "vulnerable"
    ],
    "behavior": "I replay the conversation in my mind, analyzing what I said and how they reacted. I avoid reaching out to HR or discussing my concerns with my supervisor. I withdraw from work-related communications to protect myself from further judgment.",
    "rationale": "The report highlights the client's 'feeling judged' during the HR interaction and describes emotional responses such as anxiety, embarrassment, and shame. It notes cognitive patterns of worrying about how they are perceived and behavioral responses like avoidance and rumination. The report also discusses the client's vulnerability and stress in managing health and work, supporting the selected beliefs and coping strategies."
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Conceptualization for Client with Recurrent Stomachaches and Anxiety",
    "id": "39-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client has a history of recurrent stomachaches and physical symptoms linked to anxiety and stress. They have previously struggled with weight management, sexuality, and academic performance, which may have contributed to feelings of shame or embarrassment. The client reports experiencing a transformation during college, suggesting a period of positive change and adaptation. Currently, they seek control in relationships, indicating a possible pattern of managing anxiety through external control. These patterns are likely to have shaped their current beliefs and coping strategies.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am a failure, loser"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I don't have control over my symptoms or get reassurance, then something bad will happen and I won't be able to cope. If I show weakness or uncertainty, others may judge me or not support me. I must always be vigilant about my health and seek certainty to feel safe.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I can't control my symptoms or get reassurance, it means I'm failing and things will never get better. If I keep struggling with these issues, it shows I'm not capable of change and my efforts are pointless.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client frequently seeks reassurance from others about their recovery, which provides temporary relief but reinforces dependency on external validation. They may also attempt to control their environment or relationships to reduce anxiety. Avoidance of uncertainty and over-monitoring of physical symptoms are likely recurring patterns.",
    "situation": "Experiencing ongoing stomach issues and seeking reassurance about recovery.",
    "auto_thought": "What if these stomach problems never go away? I need to know for sure that I'll recover or else I won't be able to handle it.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "worried",
      "tense",
      "fearful",
      "uncertain"
    ],
    "behavior": "I ask others for reassurance about my health and recovery. I check my symptoms repeatedly and look for signs of improvement. I avoid situations where I might feel worse or out of control.",
    "rationale": "\"The patient's recurrent stomachaches and physical symptoms are likely contributing to a heightened state of anxiety and stress... The ongoing stomach issues might trigger catastrophic thinking patterns, where the patient fears the worst outcomes regarding their health. The need for reassurance suggests a cognitive pattern of doubt and uncertainty about their ability to recover or manage their symptoms independently... In response to anxiety and stress, the patient may engage in behaviors such as seeking reassurance from others, which provides temporary relief but may reinforce dependency on external validation... The patient's history of seeking control in relationships may indicate a cognitive tendency towards perfectionism or a need for predictability.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Recent Move/Isolation Case",
    "id": "40-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client recently moved to a new living space, which has been a significant source of stress. They describe a difficult relationship with their mother, who is perceived as judgmental and emotionally unsupportive. Friendships have become strained, leading to increased feelings of isolation. The client has attempted to manage the move and unpacking alone, without support from friends, and is currently avoiding contact with both friends and their mother.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I ask for help or reach out, I will be judged or rejected, so it's safer to do everything on my own. If people don't offer support, it means I am not important to them. I must handle things myself to avoid being disappointed or hurt.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I can't manage everything alone and no one is there for me, it means I am truly alone and things will never get better. If I keep failing to connect, it proves I'm not worth supporting.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client avoids reaching out to friends or their mother, withdrawing from social contact to protect themselves from perceived judgment or conflict. They attempt to manage stressful tasks alone, which leads to exhaustion and reinforces their sense of isolation.",
    "situation": "Feeling exhausted after attempting to unpack without support from friends. Avoiding contact with friends and the mother.",
    "auto_thought": "No one cares enough to help me. I have to do everything by myself because I can't count on anyone.",
    "emotion": [
      "exhausted",
      "lonely",
      "anxious",
      "hurt",
      "disappointed",
      "overwhelmed"
    ],
    "behavior": "I stop responding to messages and avoid calling or texting friends and my mother. I continue unpacking alone, even though I feel drained.",
    "rationale": "\"The lack of support from friends during this transition may exacerbate feelings of loneliness and isolation.\" \"The patient's relationship with their mother, characterized by judgment and lack of emotional support, may lead to feelings of inadequacy, disappointment, and hurt.\" \"The patient is currently avoiding contact with friends and their mother, which may be a coping mechanism to protect themselves from perceived judgment or conflict.\" \"The stress of the move and the lack of support could lead to thoughts like 'I have to do everything myself' or 'No one cares about me,' which can contribute to feelings of helplessness and hopelessness.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "CBT Cognitive Conceptualization for Punctuality and Social Relationships",
    "id": "41-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The patient has a complex relationship history, especially involving Cricket, which has disrupted their social circle and may have led to feelings of isolation or exclusion. They frequently adopt a caretaking role, particularly with Lucy, who has ongoing medical issues, suggesting a pattern of prioritizing others' needs. These dynamics appear to contribute to emotional distress and may reinforce self-doubt and a sense of responsibility for others' well-being.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned",
      "I am bound to be rejected"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I am not always available and reliable for others, they will think less of me or leave me out. I must meet others' expectations to maintain my place in my social circle. If I fail to be on time or supportive, it means I am not a good friend.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I keep failing to meet expectations, it just proves that I'm not good enough and nothing I do will change how others see me. No matter how hard I try, I end up letting people down, so there's no point in trying.",
    "coping_strategies": "The patient often takes on a caretaking role to feel needed and valued, sometimes neglecting their own needs. They may procrastinate or become distracted, leading to running late, which temporarily avoids anxiety but perpetuates guilt and stress. Withdrawal or avoidance of certain social situations may also occur due to relationship complexities.",
    "situation": "Running late for appointments and social gatherings, including therapy and lunches with friends.",
    "auto_thought": "I'm running late again—everyone is going to be annoyed with me. They'll think I don't care or that I'm unreliable.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "guilty",
      "embarrassed",
      "worried",
      "ashamed"
    ],
    "behavior": "I rush to get ready but keep checking the time anxiously. I consider texting to apologize or make excuses. Sometimes I avoid eye contact or withdraw when I finally arrive.",
    "rationale": "\"The patient's tendency to run late may induce feelings of guilt or embarrassment, as they might perceive themselves as letting others down or failing to meet expectations.\" \"The pattern of running late could be associated with thoughts of inadequacy or fear of judgment, potentially reinforcing a negative self-image.\" \"The patient may exhibit cognitive tendencies such as overthinking or ruminating about their relationships and social interactions.\" \"The patient appears to cope by taking on a caretaking role, which may serve as a way to feel needed and valued, potentially compensating for feelings of inadequacy in other areas.\""
  },
  {
    "name": "Anonymous Client",
    "id": "42-1",
    "type": [
      "CBT",
      "case formulation"
    ],
    "history": "The client reports recurrent dreams during graduate school about being unprepared for a thesis defense, indicating longstanding anxiety about performance and fear of not meeting expectations. The client's father is described as having high expectations, which likely contributed to the development of internalized pressure to succeed and a fear of failure. These themes of anxiety and striving to meet high standards appear to persist into the client's current professional life, as evidenced by recurring dreams involving coworkers' negative judgments.",
    "helpless_belief": [
      "I am helpless",
      "I am defective",
      "I am trapped",
      "I am out of control",
      "I am powerless, weak, vulnerable",
      "I am incompetent"
    ],
    "unlovable_belief": [
      "I am unlovable",
      "I am bound to be abandoned"
    ],
    "worthless_belief": [],
    "intermediate_belief": "If I am not fully prepared or if others criticize me, it means I am failing and will be judged harshly. I must always meet high standards to avoid negative evaluation. If people talk negatively about me, it proves I am not good enough.",
    "intermediate_belief_depression": "If I can't meet expectations or if others think poorly of me, there is no point in trying because I will always fall short. No matter what I do, I will never be good enough in others' eyes.",
    "coping_strategies": "The client tends to ruminate on potential criticisms and worries about others' opinions, especially in professional contexts. They may avoid situations where they feel evaluated or seek reassurance to manage feelings of inadequacy. These strategies provide temporary relief but reinforce anxiety and self-doubt.",
    "situation": "Experiencing a recurring dream in which coworkers talk negatively about the individual.",
    "auto_thought": "My coworkers think I'm incompetent and are talking behind my back. If they see my mistakes, they'll never respect me.",
    "emotion": [
      "anxious",
      "worried",
      "insecure",
      "vulnerable",
      "ashamed"
    ],
    "behavior": "After waking from the dream, the client dwells on what coworkers might think of them. They mentally review recent work interactions, searching for signs of criticism or disapproval.",
    "rationale": "\"The patient's cognitive patterns appear to be influenced by a fear of negative evaluation and a desire to meet high standards, likely internalized from their father's expectations.\" \"The recurring dreams about being unprepared and coworkers speaking negatively may reflect a cognitive tendency to anticipate criticism and doubt one's abilities.\" \"The patient likely experiences emotions such as anxiety, worry, and fear in response to situations where they feel evaluated or judged.\" \"In response to these cognitive and emotional patterns, the patient may engage in behaviors such as ruminating on potential criticisms, avoiding situations where they might be evaluated, or seeking reassurance from others to mitigate feelings of inadequacy.\""
  },
